twork/service latency; fakes can understate tail latency. MOCK-HIDE: mocked model calls can always meet SLA and hide real timeout/queuing failures. LLM-DEP: execution passes through real AI calls; even deterministic time assertion depends on real model/API behavior. MULTI-STEP: explicitly multiple agentic steps in sequence (image model then text model then decision), so Workflow is the correct floor. Adversarial critique: if the goal were only internal orchestration overhead excluding model/API latency, System/Integration could suffice; behavior text says 'full moderation pipeline' within 5s, which includes those steps.","test_description":"Run end-to-end submissions through real image and text model calls with production-like concurrency; measure submit-to-final-decision latency and assert p95 (or required percentile) stays <= 5s.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.55}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: bug is at module boundary (model client error -> queue/retry state transition). REAL-INFRA: rejected System because behavior text does not require OS/network-specific outage semantics; injected unavailability errors can reproduce the failure. MOCK-HIDE: a mock that only returns success would hide failure, but a failure-injecting fake client exposes it. LLM-DEP: no dependence on model output quality; only error handling path. MULTI-STEP: no multi-agentic sequence requirement. Adversarial critique: real outage modes (timeouts, partial responses) may differ from injected exceptions, so a System test may still be needed for confidence.","test_description":"Use wired service + real queue/repository modules with a model client stub that returns unavailability errors; assert post enters retry queue and is n